	<article>
		<h1>Algebraic Geometry Learning Path</h1>
		
		<p>Algebraic geometry is a very important branch of modern mathematics that studies the geometric properties of systems of algebraic equations.</p>
		
		<h2>Prerequisites</h2>
		
		<p>Before learning algebraic geometry, it is recommended to master the following:</p>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Abstract Algebra</strong>: Basic theory of groups, rings, and fields</li>
			<li><strong>Commutative Algebra</strong>: Ideals, localization, Noetherian rings, etc.</li>
			<li><strong>Topology</strong>: Basic topological concepts, especially Zariski topology</li>
			<li><strong>Differential Geometry</strong> (optional but recommended): Manifolds, tangent spaces, etc.</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h2>Recommended Textbooks</h2>
		
		<h3>Beginner Level</h3>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Fulton, W.</strong> - <em>Algebraic Curves: An Introduction to Algebraic Geometry</em>
				<ul>
					<li>Starts with plane curves, progressive approach</li>
					<li>Suitable for beginners</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Reid, M.</strong> - <em>Undergraduate Algebraic Geometry</em>
				<ul>
					<li>Friendly introduction for undergraduates</li>
					<li>Contains many examples</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h3>Intermediate Level</h3>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Hartshorne, R.</strong> - <em>Algebraic Geometry</em>
				<ul>
					<li>Classic textbook, but quite abstract</li>
					<li>Recommended to read after having some foundation</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Shafarevich, I.R.</strong> - <em>Basic Algebraic Geometry</em>
				<ul>
					<li>Two volumes, comprehensive content</li>
					<li>Volume 1: Algebraic varieties, schemes</li>
					<li>Volume 2: Schemes and complex geometry</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h3>Advanced Level</h3>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>EGA</strong> (Éléments de géométrie algébrique) - Grothendieck
				<ul>
					<li>Foundational work of modern algebraic geometry</li>
					<li>Suitable for in-depth study</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h2>Learning Path</h2>
		
		<h3>Phase 1: Basic Concepts (1-2 months)</h3>
		
		<ul>
			<li>Affine and projective algebraic varieties</li>
			<li>Irreducibility and dimension</li>
			<li>Regular functions and morphisms</li>
			<li>Basic examples: lines, conic curves, cubic curves</li>
		</ul>
		
		<h3>Phase 2: Scheme Theory (2-3 months)</h3>
		
		<ul>
			<li>Definition and basic properties of schemes</li>
			<li>Sheaves and sheaf cohomology</li>
			<li>Morphisms between schemes</li>
			<li>Separatedness and finite type</li>
		</ul>
		
		<h3>Phase 3: Advanced Topics (3-6 months)</h3>
		
		<ul>
			<li>Cohomology theory</li>
			<li>Divisor theory</li>
			<li>Intersection theory</li>
			<li>Special topics: elliptic curves, K3 surfaces, etc.</li>
		</ul>
		
		<h2>Important Theorems</h2>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Hilbert's Nullstellensatz</strong>: Bridge connecting algebra and geometry</li>
			<li><strong>Riemann-Roch Theorem</strong>: Important result on curves</li>
			<li><strong>Serre Duality</strong>: Core of cohomology theory</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h2>Learning Tips</h2>
		
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Do many exercises</strong>: Algebraic geometry requires extensive computation to develop intuition</li>
			<li><strong>Draw diagrams</strong>: Even in high dimensions, low-dimensional examples are important</li>
			<li><strong>Learn commutative algebra</strong>: This is the linguistic foundation of algebraic geometry</li>
			<li><strong>Read original papers</strong>: Understand the historical background of important theorems</li>
		</ol>
		
		<h2>Online Resources</h2>
		
		<ul>
			<li><a href="https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stacks Project</a> - Complete reference for algebraic geometry</li>
			<li><a href="https://math.stanford.edu/~vakil/216blog/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Vakil's Foundations of Algebraic Geometry</a> - Excellent online textbook</li>
		</ul>
		
		<h2>Mathematical Formula Examples</h2>
		
		<p>Here are some important mathematical formulas:</p>
		
		<p>Hilbert's Nullstellensatz: If <Latex formula="I" /> is an ideal in <Latex formula="k[x_1, \\ldots, x_n]" />, then</p>
		
		<Latex formula="I(V(I)) = \\sqrt{I}" displayMode={true} />
		
		<p>Riemann-Roch Theorem (curve version): For a divisor <Latex formula="D" /> on a curve <Latex formula="C" />, we have</p>
		
		<Latex formula="\\ell(D) - \\ell(K - D) = \\deg(D) + 1 - g" displayMode={true} />
		
		<p>where <Latex formula="g" /> is the genus of the curve and <Latex formula="K" /> is the canonical divisor.</p>
	</article>
